The people who fled the violence of their homelands have now set up their tents and settled on an indefinite stretch of road between the checkpoints of two countries.
Frustration, however, grew.
While the police helicopter was standing above them, the immigrants kept saying, “Open the border,” and shouted insults to the Hungarian riot police.
Some refused food and water in protest.
Serbia's Foreign Minister declared that it is - unacceptable - the return of migrants from Hungary as more and more people arrive from Macedonia and Greece.
“(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution, not cause harm to civilians.
The debate will have to take place in the next few days with other countries and Brussels — Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The confusion on the Hungarian-Serbia border arose after a group of 28 nationalities failed to establish a common immigration policy at a controversial meeting in Brussels.
Ministers agreed on the division of responsibilities for the 40,000 asylum seekers who have now taken over Italy and Greece, and they spoke with hope of reaching a final agreement - next month or by the end of next year - on which EU countries will take 120,000 additional refugees, including some of Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria are calling for an extra EU summit next week to discuss the migration crisis on the continent.
However, Hungary does not hope that its neighbours or Brussels will be able to act soon.
Tuesday's state of emergency in two southern regions gave the authorities greater power to act in the crisis and allowed you to be closed down and asylum cases to be speeded up.
