In recent months, Hungary has become the largest bottleneck and entry point to the European Union for refugees, many of whom are fleeing war from Syria and the rest of the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has argued that the majority of those arriving are economic refugees in search of a better life, and not those fleeing from war who are entitled to protection - this view is strongly in conflict with other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, now define an attempt to cross or damage a 4-metre (13 ft) barbed wire fence built by the government on the southern border with Serbia as a crime, and include longer prison sentences for convicted human traffickers.
