Succulamados do not normally react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when surrounded by a liquid with microscopically small bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles strengthened the ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect TRP-4-ion channels, structures found in cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, reports a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To make ultrasonic controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their neurons have TRP-4-ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound on modified worms, micro bubbles strengthened sound waves and transmitted them to worms where they turn on modified motion nerve cells.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenics may have some advantages over optogenics.
Unlike light that needs to be sent along the optical fiber to the desired area within the brain, low frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
“We believe that using gene therapy and the therapeutic virus can make it possible to make the targeted human neurons react momentarily to the ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical environment,” Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
