U.S. Central Bank officials sit around a huge mahogany table for two days this week at a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise the steering rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-story meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that the President of the Central Bank, Janet L. Yellen, and his colleagues, must put the economic interests of the nation ahead of everything else.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank: they must maximise US employment and keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Depression, central bank leaders have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: economic stability.
It is this third requirement that can be a decisive factor in a decision to be published on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted, as to whether the US economy is prepared to be weaned from a record incentive that, until late 2008, has been almost zero in terms of short-term interest rates.
While most of the data show a steady growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made the central bank officials who are already on guard in advance more fearful as to increasing instability. Fearing what would happen if the federal funds rate reference value was raised by even a quarter of a percentage point.
“Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important issues to be monitored,” says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economics expert at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“I believe, however, that if they are looking for justification for restoring interest rates, the increased uncertainty in the world market is valid enough to wait,” he said.
No agreement has been reached on the decision of the Central Bank, which already causes nervousness in the economy.
According to Bloomberg’s recent study, about half of economic experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
On the other hand, the financial markets expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as a key indicator indicates that growth is only around 30%.
This suggests a decline in the securities market if the central bank does not raise the level if the decision-makers then fail to soften the blow by promising that the next withdrawal will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average increased 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, with a new number of 16,599.85.
The recovery was brought with it by the expectation that the central bank would keep the level the same this week, says John Lonski, chief financial expert at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank is raising interest rates right now,” he said.
If policymakers raise interest rates, they'll have to put a lot of effort into their policies to support the financial markets so they don't panic.
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm the financial markets as it would remove uncertainty as to when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would this month be raising interest rates by a quarter percent, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year despite the fact that the Liberals are demanding more economic development in their complaints.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1%, the lowest figure in seven years and close to the level the central bank considers to be the limit for full employment.
The increase in wages has shown signs of improvement.
Although inflation is still below the 2% annual target of the central bank, the main reason for this, according to the central bank's decision-makers, is the temporary effect of a significantly lower price of oil.
Ian Shepherdson, chief financial expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics, said in a statement: “The economy can cope with even higher interest rates and also needs them in view of the tight situation in the labour market.
However, the financial markets around the world were shaken last week as China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average index dropped as much as 16% of its May record, as investors feared that China would slow down the economy as well as slow down global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10% below the peak in May.
For central bank decision-makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in a complex equation that tells when interest rates should be raised.
“Without these financial market events and recent weeks of reporting on China’s economic weakness, policymakers would be tightening levels at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that the decision-makers will wait at least a month to get a better understanding of the impact.
“Possible effects on the US economy are still very unclear, and they don’t have much information at their disposal as regards the consequences of the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Central Bank has become the monetary authority of the world.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
In 2013, the president at the time, Ben S. Bernanken, hinted that the central bank could — narrow down — increase the amount of money, caused upheavals in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is more art than science, says Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy of Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, pointed out this month that —the central bank has previously overreacted to the financial market movement that appears to be separate from the fundamentals of the economy —
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for a raise in interest rates, and Lacker, a member of the committee entitled to vote, cites the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The economic crisis in Asia caused the Central Bank to cut its reference value by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings, despite its limited, identifiable impact on US economic growth, Lacker said.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only give priority to economic stability during the Great Crisis, as when the market collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, former member of the Bank of England interest-setting committee.
The latest turmoil does not come near its level, Posen says.
“No one wants to be in a situation where there is fear of raising interest rates because the market is getting annoyed,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a twofold demand and does not mention economic stability; as long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
