Weight Loss Surgery May Help Mildly Obese Diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after weight loss surgery than those treated in other ways than surgery.
“It takes a long time to get the mortality data,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial for the new study in JAMA Surgery.
For weight loss, or bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the subjects in the study have been morbidly obese and their BMI has been 35 or more.
The BMI, or weight ratio to length, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is over 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if the BMI is over 30, they are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of the cut persons fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, BMI remained roughly the same in 29 people treated by means other than surgery.
Of those who had surgery, 36 per cent had a complete and 28 per cent had partial improvement in diabetes.
By comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes resolved completely by only 1% and partly by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and —bad — LDL cholesterol —were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood levels of haemoglobin A1c, which reflected blood sugar levels over the long term.
Haemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers wrote.
Post-operative hemoglobin A1c levels dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at approximately 8%.
This better -- glycemic control -- described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, however, did not reduce mortality over a five-year period, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The study team also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared with the gastric reduction surgery group, the gastric bypass group had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), decreased more than its body mass index (7.4 and 5.1), decreased more than its A1c levels (3.1% and 2.1%), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 percent and 16.7%).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoneix says that although the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden where surgery led to longer life in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people undergoing weight loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die over a period of 15 years when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
Although the new study does not show any improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says that the results are encouraging for those with a BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
“The results of the study are crucial precisely in showing that surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group — and does not involve an increased risk of death or kidney disease,” he said.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously at a time when the patient’s BMI is between 27 and 30.
“I think we’re waiting too long before we take this seriously,” he said.
I believe that when a person has collected these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
