Xi calls for a wider open economy to the world
“The economy must be more open to the outside world to promote growth,” Xi Jinping told a group to guide the reform.
“China should commit itself to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency,” he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of the general reform.
Supporting transparency at the same time as reforms are driven forward to increase new movement and vitality, and creating new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Management Team adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list of market access restrictions, a loosening of border control principles, a call on state-owned enterprises to seize private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created identifying the sectors and companies in which it is not allowed to invest.
The system will be tested gradually and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant, as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more open.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to manage their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new cross-border economic cooperation models and new mechanisms for regional growth.
In order to open up sectors controlled by the state, more sectors will open up to private investors.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, the application process for foreign permanent residence permits, green cards, is facilitated by optimizing requirements and easing the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guarantee of professional rights for lawyers and the support of professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang, and senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, reported in a statement published after the meeting.
